  "text": "Action capabilities are not always constant in daily locomotor activities; they are altered when walking while holding a shopping bag or a large box. Since a wider space than usual is required for locomotion under these situations, the dimensions of an external object needs to be accurately represented by the CNS as if it were a biological extension of the body. In other words, body-scaled (or action-scaled) information needs to be recalibrated in response to the extension [CITATION_1] .",
